                    {
                        xtype: 'container',
                        html: '<p>As we move closer to the seating area, again made of recycled plastic, we can see brushed stainless steel plates with folklore stories etched upon them.  </p> <p>They are some of the local folklore and ghost stories associated with our lake. Many more can be found in the folklore commission held in Cavan Town library. Of the ghost stories and folklore associated with the lake my favourite would have to be the one of the ghost coffins floating across the lake and the story of St. Brigid’s well located on the far side of the lake under an oak tree on Boylan’s Hill.  This well is said to have the cure of warts.</p> <p>Not all story’s associated with the lake are fun, the lake has a double tragedy. Two young cousins who were training to be priests locally here in Cavan Town drowned here in 1870.  They had gone swimming for the afternoon and had gotten into trouble on their return to the bank. Sadly both cousins were lost and are buried in Annagelliffe cemetery overlooking the Green Lake.  </p> <p>We invite you to now sit and read some of our local folklore.</p>',
                        id: 'htmlPoint5',
                        styleHtmlContent: true,
                        scrollable: true
                    }
