                    {
                        xtype: 'container',
                        html: '<p>Coming up to the top of the walkway we come to a reconstructed stone wall. Build from limestone quarried in Manorstone, Moynalty, County Meath it is made with a dry motar.  </p> <p>Traditionally stone walls have to be nine fists high and three fists wide.  Stone walls apart from being a cheap and effective way of creating a boundary around your field are an important habitat for local wildlife.  Small animals including newts live in the cracks between the stones and they are protected from prey, keep warm and dry and often a well built stone wall is the perfect place for winter hibernation.</p> <p>The final part of our tour is our tree lined walkways were you can see local flora in all its glory.  The route towards Cavan Town is called Alder Walk and Willow Walk sends us back to the car park.</p> <p>We sincerely hope you enjoyed the tour of our Green Lake and we will leave you to enjoy the walkways at your leisure.</p>',
                        id: 'htmlPoint7',
                        styleHtmlContent: true,
                        scrollable: true
                    }
